Buffer management:
	DO NOT implement the buffer management of the original printf()

Handle conversions:
	%c		char		expects an argument of type 'char'
	%s		string		it expects an argument of type 'char *' pointing to the null terminated string.
	%p		pointer		print value of a pointer in hexadecimal format
						it expects an argument of type 'void*'
	%d		decimal integer		expects an argument of type 'int'
	%i		decimal integer		expects an argument of type 'int'
			the key difference between %d vs %i is how they interpret the input value
	%u		unsigned integer	expects an argument of type 'unsigned int'
	%x		Hexadecimal (lowercase)	print integers in hexadecimal format using (0-9, a-f)
								expects an argument of type 'unsigned int'
	%X	Hexadecimal (Uppercase)	as above (0-9, A-F).
